{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"30065892-76b1-457f-9907-d3978e73774e","content":"The directory doesn't exist yet, but I can answer your question directly — here's what you need to configure in your `.csproj` to publish a C# MCP server as a **dotnet tool** on NuGet.org:\n\n### Required `.csproj` properties\n\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <!-- Makes it a dotnet tool -->\n  <PackAsTool>true</PackAsTool>\n\n  <!-- The command users will run (e.g., `my-mcp-server`) -->\n  <ToolCommandName>my-mcp-server</ToolCommandName>\n\n  <!-- Must be Exe for stdio transport -->\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n\n  <!-- NuGet metadata -->\n  <PackageId>MyMcpServer</PackageId>\n  <Version>1.0.0</Version>\n  <Authors>YourName</Authors>\n  <Description>An MCP server for ...</Description>\n  <PackageReadmeFile>README.md</PackageReadmeFile>\n  <PackageLicenseExpression>MIT</PackageLicenseExpression>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n### Key points\n\n1. **`PackAsTool=true`** — this is the critical property that makes `dotnet pack` produce a tool package.\n2. **`ToolCommandName`** — the CLI command name users invoke; defaults to the assembly name if omitted.\n3. **`OutputType` must be `Exe`** — required for both stdio transport and dotnet tools.\n\n### Publish workflow\n\n```bash\n# Pack\ndotnet pack -c Release\n\n# Push to NuGet.org\ndotnet nuget push bin/Release/MyMcpServer.1.0.0.nupkg \\\n  --api-key YOUR_API_KEY \\\n  --source https://api.nuget.org/v3/index.json\n```\n\n### Users install & run it with\n\n```bash\ndotnet tool install --global MyMcpServer\nmy-mcp-server  # runs via stdio\n```\n\nWould you like me to create the project structure or update an existing `.csproj`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9028f710-f9ce-40b2-8341-28be2ef2b903","outputTokens":503,"requestId":"F04E:F615C:124F5E2:14AE8F7:69F94174"},"id":"e7c171d5-c55f-4abd-89c0-372d7427786b","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:01:51.795Z","parentId":"56a7033d-6d29-4108-946f-fdff121433a0"}
